## What Problem This Solves
Discord multi-attachment delivery was incomplete across real send paths:

- public Discord action surfaces accepted only scalar `mediaUrl`/`media` values and dropped `mediaUrls` arrays before they reached `sendMessageDiscord`;
- overflow attachment sends could retry the whole high-level delivery boundary, risking replay of already-sent batches if a later 10-file chunk failed;
- `replyToMode: "first"` was resolved before the multi-attachment send boundary, so the single-use reply could be consumed before the first actual Discord POST or applied inconsistently across overflow batches;
- component-spec Discord messages still looked as if plural media was accepted even though that path can only attach one media item, which could silently discard extra attachments.

## Why This Change Was Made
Discord allows up to 10 files per message, so OpenClaw has to split larger `mediaUrls` arrays while keeping each actual REST POST independent. This patch keeps plural `mediaUrls` intact through the public action/runtime layers, passes a lazy `replyTo` resolver into multi-media sends so the low-level POST loop consumes it per batch, and removes the high-level retry wrapper around multi-batch deliveries so the existing Discord request retry handles only the failed POST.

Component-spec messages now reject multiple media references with a targeted error instead of silently dropping attachments. Single-media, component fallback, and voice paths keep the previous string `replyTo` behavior. Voice sends still reject more than one media reference because Discord voice delivery is one file per message.

## User Impact
Users can send galleries through Discord with `mediaUrls` from both `sendMessage` and legacy `send` actions. Up to 10 attachments are sent in one Discord message; larger arrays are split into follow-up messages without losing the first reply reference.

If a transient Discord error happens on an overflow batch, OpenClaw retries that failed batch without reposting the earlier successful attachment batch. Component-spec callers now get an explicit error when they provide more than one media item, so they can switch to the multi-attachment send path instead of losing files.

## Evidence
Head commit: `112f5d4a79948509fbaf7818ea8d2d962fa48ec8`.

Local targeted behavior proof:

- `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run extensions/discord/src/send.sends-basic-channel-messages.test.ts extensions/discord/src/outbound-adapter.test.ts extensions/discord/src/actions/runtime.test.ts extensions/discord/src/actions/handle-action.test.ts` passed.
- `pnpm oxfmt --check extensions/discord/src/send.shared.ts extensions/discord/src/send.outbound.ts extensions/discord/src/outbound-payload.ts extensions/discord/src/actions/runtime.messaging.send.ts extensions/discord/src/actions/handle-action.ts extensions/discord/src/send.sends-basic-channel-messages.test.ts extensions/discord/src/outbound-adapter.test.ts extensions/discord/src/actions/runtime.test.ts extensions/discord/src/actions/handle-action.test.ts extensions/discord/src/actions/component-action-runtime.ts docs/plugins/discord-actions.md` passed.
- `pnpm tsgo:extensions:test` passed.
- `git diff --check` passed.

Behavior cases covered by tests:

- public `sendMessage` forwards `mediaUrls` arrays into `sendMessageDiscord` and clears scalar `mediaUrl` when plural media is provided;
- legacy `send` maps `mediaUrls` arrays into the Discord send action;
- 11 attachments split into 10-file and 1-file Discord POSTs;
- `replyToMode: "first"` adds `message_reference` to the first overflow POST and not the second;
- a transient failure on the second overflow batch retries only that failed batch and does not replay the first successful batch;
- component-spec messages reject multiple media refs instead of dropping all but one.

## What Problem This Solves

Issue #96542 reports that two genuinely different project directories whose paths differ only by a path separator (e.g., `client/app` vs `client-app`) get encoded to the same session directory. When a user runs `continueRecent` to resume the most recent session, it silently loads the other project's conversation history. The agent then executes tools in the requested cwd while carrying an unrelated project's transcript — with no cwd check ever catching the mismatch.

## Why This Change Was Made

Two linked defects:

1. **Non-injective encoding** in `getDefaultSessionDir`: `/`, `\`, `:` all mapped to `-`, so `client/app` and `client-app` produced the same encoded dir.
2. **No cwd verification** on resume: `findMostRecentSession` picks the newest file by mtime without checking `header.cwd` against the requested cwd.

The fix replaces the lossy mapping with percent-encoding (`/` → `%2F`, `\` → `%5C`, `:` → `%3A`, with `%` escaped first) and adds cwd verification in `continueRecent`. Only `src/agents/sessions/session-manager.ts` changed.

## Evidence

**Encoding is now injective** — colliding path pairs produce different session dirs, normal paths unchanged, percent signs escaped:

```
$ node --import tsx -e "
import { tmpdir } from 'node:os';
import { mkdirSync } from 'node:fs';
import { getDefaultSessionDir } from './src/agents/sessions/session-manager.ts';
const base = tmpdir() + '/openclaw-' + Date.now();
mkdirSync(base, { recursive: true });
const cases = [
  { label: '/ vs -', a: '/home/user/client/app', b: '/home/user/client-app' },
  { label: 'normal project', a: '/home/user/project' },
  { label: 'percent sign', a: '/home/user/100%25done' },
  { label: 'sub vs sub-', a: '/home/user/sub/proj', b: '/home/user/sub-proj' },
];
for (const c of cases) {
  const dirA = getDefaultSessionDir(c.a, base);
  if (c.b) {
    const dirB = getDefaultSessionDir(c.b, base);
    console.log(JSON.stringify({ [c.label]: { a: dirA.replace(base,'~'), b: dirB.replace(base,'~'), collision: dirA===dirB } }));
  } else {
    console.log(JSON.stringify({ [c.label]: dirA.replace(base,'~') }));
  }
}
"
{
  "/ vs -": {
    "a": "~/sessions/--home%2Fuser%2Fclient%2Fapp--",
    "b": "~/sessions/--home%2Fuser%2Fclient-app--",
    "collision": false
  }
}
{
  "normal project": "~/sessions/--home%2Fuser%2Fproject--"
}
{
  "percent sign": "~/sessions/--home%2Fuser%2F100%2525done--"
}
{
  "sub vs sub-": {
    "a": "~/sessions/--home%2Fuser%2Fsub%2Fproj--",
    "b": "~/sessions/--home%2Fuser%2Fsub-proj--",
    "collision": false
  }
}
```

**Regression tests**: 94 tests pass (2 files, including new coverage for encoding and cwd resume verification).

```
 Test Files  2 passed (2)
      Tests  94 passed (94)
```

**Format / lint**: `oxfmt --check` clean, `oxlint` clean, `git diff --check` no output.

